{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"4d9e1bb5-c9f4-4c3f-846a-3f9e38b24704","content":"**MSTest.Sdk 4.x dropped the VSTest bridge adapter by default.**\n\nIn 3.x, the SDK still bundled `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.VSTestBridge`, so `vstest.console` could discover tests. Starting with 4.0, the project builds as a standalone **Microsoft Testing Platform** executable — no VSTest adapter is included, so `vstest.console` sees zero tests.\n\n### Your options\n\n**Option A — Re-enable the VSTest bridge** (quick fix):\n\n```xml\n<Project Sdk=\"MSTest.Sdk/4.1.0\">\n  <PropertyGroup>\n    <TargetFramework>net8.0</TargetFramework>\n    <EnableMicrosoftTestingPlatformVSTestBridge>true</EnableMicrosoftTestingPlatformVSTestBridge>\n  </PropertyGroup>\n</Project>\n```\n\n**Option B — Migrate CI to `dotnet test`** (recommended long-term):\n\nReplace `vstest.console` in your pipeline with:\n\n```bash\ndotnet test TestProject.csproj\n```\n\n`dotnet test` (especially with .NET 8+ SDK) natively supports Microsoft Testing Platform executables. This is the intended path forward and avoids carrying the VSTest compatibility layer.\n\nWould you like me to update your project file with either option?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"20b06f1f-5fcc-4ec2-a14d-ca799a73a10f","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a well-known breaking change in MSTest SDK. Starting with MSTest.Sdk 3.8, the default test runner switched from VSTest to Microsoft Testing Platform (MTP). But actually, let me be more precise.\n\nMSTest.Sdk has been evolving. The key change is:\n\n- **MSTest.Sdk 3.x** (earlier versions): By default, projects used the VSTest runner infrastructure, meaning `vstest.console` could discover and run tests.\n- **MSTest.Sdk 3.3+** introduced Microsoft Testing Platform as an option.\n- **MSTest.Sdk 3.8**: Still defaulted to VSTest compatibility.\n\n\n- **MSTest.Sdk 4.0+**: The default flipped—the VSTest adapter is no longer included, so projects build as Microsoft Testing Platform executables by default and `vstest.console` can't discover tests anymore. To fix this, I can either enable the dotnet test support flag and use `dotnet test` (which works with Microsoft Testing Platform in .NET 9+ SDK), or re-enable the VSTest bridge through a project property.\n\n- The key difference between versions: MSTest.Sdk 3.x included the VSTest bridge adapter for backward compatibility even though it defaulted to the Microsoft Testing Platform, but 4.0+ dropped that adapter entirely. So the breaking change is that `vstest.console` simply won't work unless you explicitly re-enable the bridge or switch to `dotnet test`.","outputTokens":957,"requestId":"982C:2EAF75:13635A3:1861DEF:69FFF66E"},"id":"e69f8f93-8b6e-4288-8b37-a7a3e4c282af","timestamp":"2026-05-10T03:07:45.437Z","parentId":"19440056-a652-41b5-8e67-dcf57d5b0c63"}
